Part I - (Ford GoBike System Data Exploration)¶

by Baha abu khalil¶

Introduction¶

This dataset contains information about individual bike rides in the Ford GoBike bike-sharing system, covering the greater San Francisco Bay Area during February 2019. The dataset includes details like trip duration, start and end times, station names, user type (Subscriber or Customer), and more. The goal of this analysis is to explore ride patterns and differences between user types, and to uncover trends related to time, duration, and stations.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset consists of approximately 183,412 rows and multiple columns, including information about trip duration, start and end times, station names and locations, bike ID, user type (Subscriber/Customer), member birth year, and gender. Some columns contain missing data (e.g., member_birth_year has fewer non-null values). Most columns are either numeric (e.g., duration_sec, member_birth_year) or categorical (e.g., user_type, bike_id).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest are duration_sec (trip duration), user_type (Subscriber or Customer), and temporal features (such as start time and end time) to explore usage patterns.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Features like start_time, end_time, start_station_name, end_station_name, member_birth_year, and member_gender will help in understanding how trip duration and user type vary by time, location, age, and gender.

Univariate Exploration¶

Question: What is the distribution of trip duration in seconds?

Visualization: The histogram below shows the distribution of trip duration in seconds.

Observation: The distribution of trip duration is right-skewed, with most trips lasting less than 1000 seconds. There are a few trips with very long durations, but these are rare.

In [32]:
def set_plot_labels(title, x_label, y_label):
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(x_label)
    plt.ylabel(y_label)

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
bins = np.arange(0, df['duration_sec'].max()+60, 60)
plt.hist(df['duration_sec'], bins=bins)
set_plot_labels('Distribution of Trip Duration', 'Duration (seconds)', 'Count')
plt.xlim(0, 5000)
plt.show()

Question:¶

What is the distribution of user types (Subscriber vs Customer)?

Observation:¶

The majority of users are Subscribers, while Customers form a smaller portion of the users.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of trip duration is right-skewed, with most trips lasting less than 1000 seconds. There are a few unusual points where the duration is very long, indicating rare cases of unusually extended trips. No transformations were applied at this stage, but extreme values were noted for potential further cleaning.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Yes, the trip duration feature had a long tail with some unusually high values. While no operations were performed at this stage, these values might require further attention (e.g., filtering or transformation) during later stages of analysis to prevent distortion of summary statistics and visualizations.

Multivariate Exploration¶

Question:¶

How does trip duration vary across user type and gender?

Observation:¶

From the facet grid, we can see that for both user types, males generally make up the majority of trips. For each gender group, Customers tend to have longer trip durations compared to Subscribers. The distributions are right-skewed, and the majority of trips are under 1000 seconds across all groups.

In [40]:
import seaborn as sb

# Create a FacetGrid with user_type as column and member_gender as row
g = sb.FacetGrid(data=df, col='user_type', row='member_gender', height=4, margin_titles=True)

# Map a histogram of trip duration to the grid with bin size of 100 up to 5000
g.map(plt.hist, 'duration_sec', bins=np.arange(0, 5000+100, 100))

# Set axis labels
g.set_axis_labels('Trip Duration (sec)', 'Count')

# Set x-axis limit for clarity
g.set(xlim=(0, 5000))

# Display the plot
plt.show()

Observation:¶

From the facet grid, we can see that for both user types, males generally make up the majority of trips. For each gender group, Customers tend to have longer trip durations compared to Subscribers. The distributions are right-skewed, and the majority of trips are under 1000 seconds across all groups.

# Set axis labels
g.set_axis_labels('User Type', 'Trip Duration (sec)')

# Set y-axis limit for clarity
plt.ylim(0, 5000)

# Set title
plt.title('Trip Duration by User Type and Gender')

# Display the plot
plt.show()

Observation:¶

The Plot Matrix reveals several key insights:

  • Trip Duration is highly right-skewed, indicating that most trips are short, with a few long-duration outliers.
  • There appears to be a clustering of trips around working hours (7 AM - 9 AM and 4 PM - 6 PM), especially among users born between 1980 and 2000.
  • Birth year vs. Trip Duration shows that younger users tend to have more consistent and shorter trip durations.
  • No strong linear correlation is observed between the variables, but distinct patterns and groupings are visible.

df['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['start_time'])

sb.pairplot(data=plot_df, diag_kind='hist')

plt.suptitle('Plot Matrix: Trip Duration, Start Hour, and Birth Year', y=1.02)

plt.show()

Observation:¶

This scatterplot illustrates how trip duration varies by the hour of the day, differentiated by user type and gender. We observe that:

  • Most trips occur during typical commuting hours (around 8 AM and 5 PM).
  • Subscribers dominate these peak periods, suggesting regular usage patterns likely for work.
  • Customers are more scattered throughout the day with slightly longer trip durations.
  • The difference in trip patterns between genders is subtle but noticeable through marker styles.
  • Most trip durations remain below 5000 seconds, reinforcing previous findings from other plots.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

From the multivariate exploration, I observed that both user type and member gender provided complementary insights when analyzing trip duration. Specifically, the combination of user type and gender helped highlight that Customers, especially female customers, tend to have longer trip durations compared to Subscribers. This strengthened the understanding that user type alone was not sufficient — gender provided additional context to explain variations in trip duration.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

One surprising interaction was that while Subscribers generally had shorter trip durations, male subscribers still showed a slightly wider spread in their trip durations compared to female subscribers. Additionally, the “Other” gender category had very few records, but still followed a similar pattern of short trip durations among Subscribers. This highlighted how the effect of user type was dominant across gender groups.

Conclusions¶

In this data exploration project, I analyzed the Ford GoBike dataset focusing on trip durations, user types, and member gender. The univariate exploration showed that trip durations are right-skewed, with most trips lasting under 1000 seconds. The bivariate exploration revealed that customers generally take longer trips than subscribers, and that gender has a minor influence, with male users representing the majority of trips.

In the multivariate exploration, I found that combining user type and gender gave a clearer picture: male customers had the longest trip durations, while subscribers, regardless of gender, tended to take shorter trips. These insights help understand usage patterns and could inform operational decisions for the bike-sharing system.
